External editor path should be VScode path right?

Yes 👍—if you want to use an external editor in Keyman Developer, then setting it to VS Code is exactly right.

🔹 What “External Editor Path” means
It’s just telling Keyman:

“When I click ‘Edit externally’, open this program.”

So you point it to:
👉 Visual Studio Code (Code.exe)

🔹 Typical VS Code path (Windows)
Most common install locations:

Option 1 (default)
C:\Users\YOURNAME\AppData\Local\Programs\Microsoft VS Code\Code.exe
Option 2 (system install)
C:\Program Files\Microsoft VS Code\Code.exe
🔹 How to set it in Keyman
Open Keyman Developer

Go to:

Tools → Options
Find:

External Editor
Paste your VS Code path

Apply / OK

🔹 What happens after this
Now when you:

Right-click .kmn

Choose Edit externally

👉 It opens in VS Code instantly

And when you save in VS Code:

Keyman automatically sees changes (on compile)

🔹 Small recommendation (important)
Even though VS Code is great, for your case:

👉 Still compile inside Keyman Developer
because it:

catches .kmn syntax errors better

manages keyboard packaging

handles touch layout integration

🔹 Best workflow for you
VS Code → writing/editing

Keyman → compiling + testing + install

If you want next, I can help you set up:

VS Code highlighting for .kmn

auto-compile shortcuts

or a clean workflow for your Ëünic'han project so it feels like a real language dev environment 👍


Tick "Open keyboard files in source view"?

Yes 👍—you should tick “Open keyboard files in source view” in Keyman Developer, especially for what you’re building.

🔹 What that option actually does
When enabled:

.kmn files open as plain text (source code)

You can directly edit your rules (like the ones we wrote)

You see everything clearly: mappings, digraphs, logic

When disabled:

It may open a more limited or graphical view

Harder to edit complex rules like yours

