We also need to fix apostrophe as it can show up in between any two letters to make it sound separate. For example in English it could be in S'how (s-hoe-w), Portuguese Jo'a'o (jo-ah-oh), etc. It just shows the two sounds (one before it, one after are seperate and neither bleed into each other, nor create a new sound)

Yes—this is an important refinement, and you’re actually describing a real phonological separator rule (a “disjunction marker”). Your apostrophe is no longer punctuation—it becomes a sound boundary operator.

Good design choice.

🔹 What you want (formally)
Your apostrophe ' should:

Separate two letters so they stay phonologically independent,
preventing:

blending into digraphs (like ch, th, se)

forming new sounds

coalescing into ligatures

🔹 The correct way to implement this in Keyman Developer
Keyman doesn’t “interpret sound”, it processes input rules, so we enforce this structurally.

🔷 1. Make apostrophe a true “neutral separator”
We explicitly tell the keyboard:

Rule:
' does NOT transform anything

it blocks digraph rules

it passes through as itself

✔ CORE FIX
Add this:

+ ''' > '''
That keeps it visible and preserved.

🔷 2. Fix digraph interference (THIS is the key part)
Right now you have rules like:

ch → /tʃ/

th → /θ/

se → /z/

We must prevent apostrophe from triggering those.

✔ PROPER STRUCTURE (important)
We redefine digraphs to ONLY trigger when uninterrupted:

+ 'c' + 'h' > 'ch'
+ 't' + 'h' > 'th'
+ 's' + 'e' > 'se'
Then override with apostrophe:

+ 'c' + ''' + 'h' > 'c''h'
+ 't' + ''' + 'h' > 't''h'
+ 's' + ''' + 'e' > 's''e'
🔷 3. Your linguistic rule (what you just defined)
You are formalizing:

🔹 Apostrophe = phoneme boundary marker
Meaning:

Input	Output	Behavior
sh	/ʃ/ (if you define it)	merges
s'h	s + h	separated
jo'a'o	jo + a + o	no merging
c'h	c + h	NOT ch
🔷 4. Your examples (validated)
English-style:
s'how → s + how (no “sh” sound)

Portuguese-style:
Jo'a'o → Jo + a + o (no contraction)

This is exactly:

phoneme isolation rule

🔷 5. IMPORTANT DESIGN UPDATE FOR YOUR SYSTEM
We now define 3 layers:

🔹 Layer 1: Digraphs (only without apostrophe)
ch → /tʃ/

th → /θ/

se → /z/ (your system)

🔹 Layer 2: Apostrophe override
c'h → c + h

s'e → s + e

🔹 Layer 3: Everything else = raw phonemes
🔷 6. CLEAN FINAL RULE YOU SHOULD ADD
Put this in your .kmn:

+ ''' > '''

+ 'c' + 'h' > 'ch'
+ 't' + 'h' > 'th'
+ 's' + 'e' > 'se'

+ 'c' + ''' + 'h' > 'c''h'
+ 't' + ''' + 'h' > 't''h'
+ 's' + ''' + 'e' > 's''e'
🔷 7. WHY THIS IS LINGUISTICALLY STRONG
You just created:

✔ a phoneme separator system
used in:

phonetic transcription systems

constructed languages

linguistic notation

It prevents:

false digraph formation

unintended sound merging

ambiguity in pronunciation

🔷 8. IMPORTANT NOTE (this matters)
Your apostrophe is now:

NOT punctuation
NOT spacing
NOT optional symbol

It is:

👉 a phonological operator

